Half an hour later, he'd finished a blazing fast, but quite thorough, reading of Martin Eeny's life, and the frothiness thereof, and he didn't like what he'd read. At first he'd read with delighted eagerness; everything was lining up. Mr. Eeny checked all the boxes: motive, means, opportunity. While Reginald hadn't known him by name, they were clearly of the same world. Martin had had the ear of the Imperial Aviation Administration, shifty eyes, and the hands of a working man. The unions respected a man with 10 fingers. Detailed analysis of his upbringing suggested latent moral principles which could easily have led Martin Eeny to first amass power and then turn it against him in favor of The Continents. Those blasted Continents.

The problem was, Reginald didn't buy it. He would have loved to believe that through the very carelessness with which he'd thrown his glass he had decisively cut off his secret enemy, but a few important details didn't add up. First, the very notion that Eeny harbored secret continentalist sympathies hinged on the unsubstantiated account of his days as a schoolboy at Wilhelmchester School for Boys, and particularly his exposure to one Lars Squiggle[^lars], a teacher there at the time. The dossier presented a number of anonymous posts on schoolface.con which corroborated Martin's presence there, and one that told of a special mentor-mentee relationship between Squiggle and Eeny. It told of them taking long walks together. But Reginald, unknown to almost anyone, had hate-visited that school in disguise just a year prior to Eeny's arrival (to learn their ways), and had found Squiggle nearly immobile. His knees were shot from grashing, and while he could hobble to and fro, he certainly wasn't going on any long walks!

He tried to remember if he'd heard anything about Squiggle since then, seen any footage of his gait. Squiggle had mysteriously disappeared in the year 0x8eb, two years after the Eenies got rich, moved to The Islands, and got Martin a proper private tutor. It was hard to believe Squiggle would have got his knees replaced, staunch anticyberneticist that he was (though many an anticyberneticist has changed his tune when faced with crippledom), so Reginald had to assume, in the absence of further evidence, that the rumor of long walks and talks was spurious.

It may seem like a small thing, but Manuel Ordinator Computer Gonzalez was a meticulous researcher, and imprecisions like this were practically unheard of. Combined with a few other weak points in the case, which Reginald could only identify thanks to his many bold, secretive, and improbable exploits, he began to suspect this dossier had been intentionally tampered with. He felt... fear.

